Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. (Save potatoes for another use.)

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon} and half the @OLD BAY® seasoning{1%unit}. Season lightly with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: No need to season generously—there's already salt and pepper in the seasoning!

Roast on top rack until browned and crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Swap in broccoli for potatoes; roast until browned and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, heat a large drizzle of oil in a medium, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add @sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings) and a splash of @water{}; cook until onion is caramelized and jammy, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #small bowl{}.

Meanwhile, in a second small bowl, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @ketchup{2%tablespoon}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, and as much remaining Old Bay Seasoning as you like. Set aside.

Form @ground pork{10%ounce} into two equal-size balls (four balls for 4 servings); season all over with salt and pepper.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for onion over medium-high heat. Once pan is hot, add pork. Firmly flatten each ball with a #spatula{} to create very thin patties. (TIP: Do so carefully; oil may splatter a bit.) Cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-7%minutes} per side. (Don't worry if the patties aren't perfectly round—those irregular edges will turn crispy.)

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top patties with @white cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}; cover pan to melt cheese. Remove from heat.

While patties cook, halve and toast @potato buns{2}.

Divide buns between plates and fill with patties, caramelized onion, and half the special sauce. Serve burgers with Old Bay fries on the side and remaining special sauce for dipping.